is lived and enacted in everyday practice and how it reflects people’s aspirations for new futures. In a series of ethnographic case studies ranging from the Americas to the Middle East to South Asia, they examine the means of avoiding the political and historical capture that make one complicit with sovereign authority rather than creating the conditions of possibility to confront it. The contributors attend to the affective dimensions of these practices of world-building to illuminate the epistemological, ontological, and transnational entanglements that produce a sense of what is possible. They also trace how sovereignty is activated and deactivated over the course of a lifetime within the struggle of the everyday. In so doing, they outline how individuals create and enact forms of sovereignty that allow them to endure fast and slow forms of violence while embracing endless opportunities for building new worlds.Contributors. Alex Blanchette, Yarimar Bonilla, Jessica Cattelino, María Elena García, Akhil Gupta, Lochlann Jain, Purnima Mankekar, Joseph Masco, Michael Ralph, Danilyn Rutherford, Arjun Shankar, Kristen L. Simmons, Deborah A. Thomas, Leniqueca A. Welcome, Kaya Naomi Williams, Jessica Winegar  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 0aAffect (Psychology)xPolitical aspects. 0aAffect (Psychology)xSocial aspects. 0aPolitics and culture. 0aSocial structurexPolitical aspects. 0aSovereigntyxSocial aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aBlanchette, Alex, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBonilla, Yarimar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCattelino, Jessica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarcía, María Elena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 